features, supposedly,

00:15:40.230 --> 00:15:46.280
will be more easily discernible
to the naked European eye and ear.

00:15:46.280 --> 00:15:48.630
Jones proceeds to illustrate
his method.

00:15:48.630 --> 00:15:52.390
To bring an alien orient into
comparison with a familiar west,

00:15:52.390 --> 00:15:55.820
he translates two odes,
one from Persian by Hafez,

00:15:55.820 --> 00:16:00.000
the other from Latin by Horace
and [inaudible] opposes these.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.520
Having done so, he
conceives that the reader

00:16:02.520 --> 00:16:04.900
who does not know the
original expressions

00:16:04.900 --> 00:16:07.930
and the literary traditions
of these poems will fail

00:16:07.930 --> 00:16:10.710
to grasp the felicity
of their expressions

00:16:10.710 --> 00:16:13.520 position:56%
and the elegance of their illusions.

00:16:13.520 --> 00:16:17.790
Yet he insists that any such reader
can look at Hafez and Horace,

00:16:17.790 --> 00:16:21.220
reduced to plain to French,
and decide ultimately

00:16:21.220 --> 00:16:25.320
which of the two odes is the more
poetic, a quality he premises on,

00:16:25.320 --> 00:16:27.970
what he calls, charming simplicity.

00:16:27.970 --> 00:16:31.610
While he says that it is not up to
him to decide, he drops heavy hints

00:16:31.610 --> 00:16:36.300
in favor of the Persian,
but when the comparativist

00:16:36.300 --> 00:16:40.040
or translator breaks language
down into, what we might call,

00:16:40.040 --> 00:16:44.520
molecular units, hear
words, where does style go.

00:16:44.520 --> 00:16:49.140
Jones wants the European reader to
hear the music of oriental poetry,

00:16:49.140 --> 00:16:52.190
yet translation pressed into
the service of comparison,

00:16:52.190 --> 00:16:55.030
what it would seem, reduce
the unique musical phrasing

00:16:55.030 --> 00:16:58.980
of the Persian and the Latin
respectively to mere strings

00:16:58.980 --> 00:17:00.790
of common simplified,

00:17:00.790 --> 00:17:04.870
de-contextualized notes
more readily exchangeable.

00:17:04.870 --> 00:17:07.930
To demonstrate the aesthetic
value of oriental literatures

00:17:07.930 --> 00:17:11.890
to the European reader, Jones
ultimately must prove the soundness

00:17:11.890 --> 00:17:15.140
in all senses of their
languages, that is the sounds

00:17:15.140 --> 00:17:18.340
of those languages are
melodious enough to merit

00:17:18.340 --> 00:17:21.790
and justify the name poetry.

00:17:21.790 --> 00:17:23.860 position:56%
Translating the sense of the Persian

00:17:23.860 --> 00:17:28.390
into common French words is
not adequate to that task.

00:17:28.390 --> 00:17:32.400 position:56%
Thus Jones goes onto
transliterate into Roman characters,

00:17:32.400 --> 00:17:36.440
the Persian ode by Hafez that he
has just translated and placed

00:17:36.440 --> 00:17:39.600
in comparison with the
Latin ode by Horace.

00:17:39.600 --> 00:17:44.430 position:56%
What is striking here is the apology
that follows this transliteration

00:17:44.430 --> 00:17:48.560
and I quote from Jones, "Although
one should only judge the sweetness

00:17:48.560 --> 00:17:51.240
of the language by the ear,
we fear that the majority

00:17:51.240 --> 00:17:55.810
of readers were appreciated by the
eye and that they will be put off

00:17:55.810 --> 00:17:59.050
by the frequency of consonants and
of hard letters [foreign language]

00:17:59.050 --> 00:18:04.560 position:56%
that they will there, but the organ,
i.e., the tongue articulates the

00:18:04.560 --> 00:18:08.310
"huz" as easily as it
does any other consonant.

00:18:08.310 --> 00:18:14.140 position:56%
It is the Tuscan pronunciation of
'ch and of 'c' in the word, 'cavalo,

00:18:14.140 --> 00:18:16.660
which has something
very gentle about it

00:18:16.660 --> 00:18:19.360
when it is not too affected."

00:18:19.360 --> 00:18:25.200
Thus the Persian "kh," it's
transliterated as "kh,"

00:18:25.200 --> 00:18:27.980
which appears once
in the word, "khulk,"

00:18:27.980 --> 00:18:32.320
which in Arabic means temperament,
in the transliterated ode,

00:18:32.320 --> 00:18:39.280
is assimilated to the Tuscan "ch"
or hard "c" like the "c" in cavolo,

00:18:39.280 --> 00:18:46.590
where it's not a "ch," but it's an
attempt to render the sound "ch."

00:18:46.590 --> 00:18:50.070
From common sense and
sensibility, we enter the province

00:18:50.070 --> 00:18:53.420
of common sound, the
comparison of letters.

00:18:53.420 --> 00:18:55.700
Literature, is rooted
here in the letter,

00:18:55.700 --> 00:18:59.130
a common denominator more radical
than the word, a written character

00:18:59.130 --> 00:19:04.150
or grapheme, who shared spoken
or forcibly shared spoken

00:19:04.150 --> 00:19:08.290
or phoneme the European
reader is invited to hear.

00:19:08.290 --> 00:19:12.320
With his turn to the speech of
Tuscany, the dialect of Dante,

00:19:12.320 --> 00:19:15.390
to bring the literatures of the
Arabic- Islamic orient to life

00:19:15.390 --> 00:19:18.850
for the European reader, Jones
inaugurates, perhaps in spite

00:19:18.850 --> 00:19:21.630
of himself, a new tendency
in the discourse

00:19:21.630 --> 00:19:23.970
of European literary comparison.

00:19:23.970 --> 00:19:26.310
That tendency would
replace orient with occident

00:19:26.310 --> 00:19:28.610
as its fundamental model.

00:19:39.370 --> 00:19:44.480
In comparative literature 1886, the
first English language monograph

00:19:44.480 --> 00:19:47.360
to explicitly articulate
the nature and the method

00:19:47.360 --> 00:19:51.250
of the modern discipline, the
Irish barrister and classist,

00:19:51.250 --> 00:19:53.780
Hutchinson McCauley Pasnet
[phonetically spelled] traced the

00:19:53.780 --> 00:19:58.690
root of comparative literary method
to Dante's De vulgari Eloquentia

00:19:58.690 --> 00:20:03.800
on "Eloquence in the Vernacular,"
written between 1302 and 1305,

00:20:03.800 --> 00:20:07.880
which argued that the time had come
for the spoken dialect of Tuscany

00:20:07.880 --> 00:20:09.880
to [inaudible] with,
if not suppliant,

00:20:09.880 --> 00:20:12.400
Latin as a language of writing.

00:20:12.400 --> 00:20:15.030
And here I show you the particular
edition that happens to be

00:20:15.030 --> 00:20:17.850
in the Rare Books Collection
of the Library of Congress.

00:20:17.850 --> 00:20:21.860
There are many such editions, of
course, in libraries elsewhere

00:20:21.860 --> 00:20:28.260
but this one was owned by Walt
Whitman and there is a little card

00:20:28.260 --> 00:20:32.790
from I think the old card
catalog, or replica thereof,

00:20:32.790 --> 00:20:38.110
which shows that Walt Whitman
listed the half title pages,

00:20:38.110 --> 00:20:42.410
listed all of the pages where his
name appeared in Pasnet's study

00:20:42.410 --> 00:20:49.390
of comparative literature, so our
typical egocentrism is at work.

00:20:49.390 --> 00:20:56.650 position:56%
You will see that volume was part of
an international scientific series,

00:20:56.650 --> 00:20:59.930 position:56%
which is interesting in terms of the
placement of comparative literature

00:20:59.930 --> 00:21:06.310 position:56%
in the modern 19th century sciences.

00:21:06.310 --> 00:21:12.800
So I quote now from Pasnet from the
relevant passage, where he speaks

00:21:12.800 --> 00:21:15.770
of Dante's De Vulgari Eloquentia."

00:21:15.770 --> 00:21:20.970 position:56%
"When Dante wrote the "Eloquial
Vulgari, this is Pasnet's reference,

00:21:20.970 --> 00:21:23.660
it's usually called either,
"De Vulgari Eloquial,"

00:21:23.660 --> 00:21:27.220
or "De Vulgari Eloquentia," he
marked the starting the point

00:21:27.220 --> 00:21:30.480
of our modern comparative
science, the nature of language,

00:21:30.480 --> 00:21:34.570
a problem not be lightly overlooked
by the peoples of modern Europe,

00:21:34.570 --> 00:21:38.960
inheriting unlike Greek or
Hebrew, a literature written

00:21:38.960 --> 00:21:43.580 position:56%
in a tongue whose decomposition had
plainly gone to make up the elements

00:21:43.580 --> 00:21:46.280
of their own living speech.

00:21:46.280 --> 00:21:49.330
The Latin, followed at an
interval by the Greek renaissance,

00:21:49.330 --> 00:21:51.940
laid the foundations of
comparative reflection

00:21:51.940 --> 00:21:55.590
in the mind of modern Europe."

00:21:55.590 --> 00:22:00.290 position:56%
Pasnet rightly identifies the nature
of language a key starting point

00:22:00.290 --> 00:22:04.330
of modern comparative literature,
yet not just any language;

00:22:04.330 --> 00:22:07.550
for Pasnet invokes as a key
force that throws language

00:22:07.550 --> 00:22:12.100
and literature open to comparative
reflection as he calls it "The rise

00:22:12.100 --> 00:22:16.610
of modern Italian or French,"
once spoken variance of Latin,

00:22:16.610 --> 00:22:19.800
the written lingual Franca of
western Europe as languages

00:22:19.800 --> 00:22:22.130
of writing in their own right.

00:22:22.130 --> 00:22:25.280
Thus a particular register
of language, the vernacular,

00:22:25.280 --> 00:22:27.920
grounds the literature
that comes to be defined

00:22:27.920 --> 00:22:31.240
as the proper object
of modern comparison.

00:22:31.240 --> 00:22:34.390
To enter the zone of the modern
comparison, as Pasnet defines it,

00:22:34.390 --> 00:22:39.200
it seems, a literature must be
living speech, realized in writing.

00:22:39.200 --> 00:22:43.190
In the language of a comparable
literature, death can only survive

00:22:43.190 --> 00:22:45.790
if it is an intrinsic part of life.

00:22:45.790 --> 00:22:50.330 position:56%
Death must be transmuted into dying,
decomposition and it must also,

00:22:50.330 --> 00:22:55.420 position:56%
in being so transmuted, reconstitute
the living in perpetuity.

00:22:55.420 --> 00:22:57.120
Forms of language that precede

00:22:57.120 --> 00:23:00.770
and exceed living speech
suddenly seem a waste of breath.

00:23:00.770 --> 00:23:04.350
It is not that language is
inassimilable to living speech,

00:23:04.350 --> 00:23:07.490
don't breath; they do even
their respirations are

00:23:07.490 --> 00:23:09.520
sometimes unvocalized.

00:23:09.520 --> 00:23:11.700
In this regime of the
modern of comparison

00:23:11.700 --> 00:23:13.720
of literature, they can't breath.

00:23:13.720 --> 00:23:16.740
They're not allowed to breath.

00:23:16.740 --> 00:23:19.880
I turn the page now
one century earlier

00:23:19.880 --> 00:23:21.630
to Vulni's [phonetically spelled]

00:23:21.630 --> 00:23:24.970
"Simplicacion de [inaudible]
oriental," "Simplification

00:23:24.970 --> 00:23:30.750
of oriental languages," published
in Paris in 1795, a text that,

00:23:30.750 --> 00:23:33.360
as I have also learned in
the Rare Books collection

00:23:33.360 --> 00:23:36.660
of the library Thomas Jefferson
once owned and Jefferson, in fact,

00:23:36.660 --> 00:23:42.150 position:56%
owned many works by the [inaudible]
Vulni who voyaged, in fact, to Egypt

00:23:42.150 --> 00:23:46.690
and Sierra in the 1780s
and writes another text

00:23:46.690 --> 00:23:50.440
on that series of travel.

00:23:50.440 --> 00:23:53.310
In addition to the
rise of the vernacular,

00:23:53.310 --> 00:23:56.820
Pasnet noted the European
discovery of the new world

00:23:56.820 --> 00:23:59.170
as a decisive element
in the emergence

00:23:59.170 --> 00:24:03.310
of modern comparative sensibility;
yet in Vulni's estimation,

00:24:03.310 --> 00:24:07.130
Europe did not need to voyage
so far away to discover the sort

00:24:07.130 --> 00:24:11.270
of radical difference that
awakens the impulse of comparison.

00:24:11.270 --> 00:24:12.570
It's familiar.

00:24:12.570 --> 00:24:15.330
The Arabic-Islamic
world was, in many ways,

00:24:15.330 --> 00:24:17.580
its most radically foreign.

00:24:17.580 --> 00:24:22.650 position:56%
A dividing line of contrast has
stubbornly persevered, Vulni writes,

00:24:22.650 --> 00:24:25.320
"For many centuries
between the Asiatics,

00:24:25.320 --> 00:24:28.770
above all the Arabs
and European peoples.

00:24:28.770 --> 00:24:32.990 position:56%
We are separated by only 60 nautical
hours from Algeria and from Tunis,

00:24:32.990 --> 00:24:36.510
just 14 days take us to
Egypt, to Syria, to Greece,

00:24:36.510 --> 00:24:39.460
18 to Constantinople
and yet one would say

00:24:39.460 --> 00:24:45.170
that these peoples inhabit another
planet that, though contemporaries,

00:24:45.170 --> 00:24:48.140
we live separated by
several centuries.

00:24:48.140 --> 00:24:49.440
The crude observer,

00:24:49.440 --> 00:24:50.990
Luvir [phonetically spelled] Kharf
[phonetically spelled] is content

00:24:50.990 --> 00:24:54.190
to see as the reason for these
contrasts, the difference

00:24:54.190 --> 00:24:57.510
between religions, [inaudible]
customs, but this difference,

00:24:57.510 --> 00:25:01.940 position:56%
itself, has its causes and one finds
that the most powerful, indeed,

00:25:01.940 --> 00:25:03.840
perhaps the only such cause,

00:25:03.840 --> 00:25:06.350
consists of the difference
of languages."

00:25:06.350 --> 00:25:09.220
End of quote.

00:25:09.220 --> 00:25:12.300 position:56%
While various points in the
Ottoman empire are within short sail

00:25:12.300 --> 00:25:16.910
from Europe and all seem on the
surface temporarily proximate,

00:25:16.910 --> 00:25:19.560
[foreign language], contemporaries,
they are to borrow the phrase

00:25:19.560 --> 00:25:22.720
of Johanna Fabian in
"Time and the Other,"

00:25:22.720 --> 00:25:24.490
denied co-evilness with Europe.

00:25:24.490 --> 00:25:28.550
They're not allowed to occupy the
same time, the same chronology.

00:25:28.550 --> 00:25:31.700
The most spatially proximate is
the most historically distant,

00:25:31.700 --> 00:25:35.580
separated by centuries and the
historical gulf between is measured

00:25:35.580 --> 00:25:39.430
and fathomed in through and as
language in the nautical mile

00:25:39.430 --> 00:25:42.850
of a vernacular vision of language.

00:25:42.850 --> 00:25:46.310
And I quote again from Vulni, "I
account for little the contrast

00:25:46.310 --> 00:25:49.450
and the movement of Arabic script,
which while we trace our lines

00:25:49.450 --> 00:25:52.960 position:56%
from left to right, traces its own
from right to left and begins a book

00:25:52.960 --> 00:25:57.200
where we finish it, but a third
difficulty, the most serious,

00:25:57.200 --> 00:26:01.760
the most radical, is its
alphabetic system, itself.

00:26:01.760 --> 00:26:04.840
It is the incomplete,
indeed, perverted,"

00:26:04.840 --> 00:26:07.420
the word used here is
[foreign language],

00:26:07.420 --> 00:26:12.700
which has a strong moral
cast, "indeed perverted manner

00:26:12.700 --> 00:26:16.620
in which Arabic depicts
the spoken word,"

00:26:16.620 --> 00:26:20.550
and the phrase is [foreign
language].

00:26:20.550 --> 00:26:24.140
In our languages of Europe, every
element of that word, vowel,

00:26:24.140 --> 00:26:28.180
consonant, aspiration, all is
painted or depicted with detail,

00:26:28.180 --> 00:26:32.940
precision, scruple and clear
images pass through to the minds.

00:26:32.940 --> 00:26:35.820
We even regard a language as
all the more perfect in so far

00:26:35.820 --> 00:26:40.070
as its script more exactly paints
or depicts all of its pronunciation

00:26:40.070 --> 00:26:45.800
as that language is
written as it is pronounced.

00:26:45.800 --> 00:26:48.710
By contrast, Arabic and its
analogue, [inaudible], Persian,

00:26:48.710 --> 00:26:51.860
Turkish, not only does one
not write as one speaks

00:26:51.860 --> 00:26:55.380
but one writes really half
of one's words in the main,

00:26:55.380 --> 00:26:58.620
only consonants are outlined,
which are its principle base

00:26:58.620 --> 00:27:03.230 position:56%
