00:30:56.110 --> 00:31:01.060
and its kin are inorganic
and mineral.

00:31:01.060 --> 00:31:03.220
Everywhere," he writes, "an
ancient language gives way

00:31:03.220 --> 00:31:09.410
to a vernacular [foreign language],
modern dialect corresponding

00:31:09.410 --> 00:31:12.280
to a progression of analysis,
clearer more explicit,

00:31:12.280 --> 00:31:15.970
separately that which the ancient
assembled, breaking the mechanisms

00:31:15.970 --> 00:31:18.660
of the former language
to grant to each idea

00:31:18.660 --> 00:31:22.640
and to each relation its
isolated expression."

00:31:22.640 --> 00:31:25.940
"Formal Arabic," Raunak
suggests, " is an exception.

00:31:25.940 --> 00:31:29.290
It has not evolved toward the
modern dialect, the vernacular.

00:31:29.290 --> 00:31:32.260
Arabic is in a word 'o compose.'

00:31:32.260 --> 00:31:36.910
Failing to decompose, as vegetal
life does, into isolated fragments,

00:31:36.910 --> 00:31:40.720
Arabic and its Semitic cousins
supposedly have not followed the

00:31:40.720 --> 00:31:44.450
natural way of language toward
simplification but held fast

00:31:44.450 --> 00:31:48.510
for a problematic complexity,
read artificiality."

00:31:48.510 --> 00:31:50.760
And I quote again from Raunak,

00:31:50.760 --> 00:31:53.120
"This ancient of decomposition
is entirely missing

00:31:53.120 --> 00:31:54.420
from Semitic languages.

00:31:54.420 --> 00:31:56.680
No a single letter has been lost.

00:31:56.680 --> 00:31:59.300
Guarded by closed and
precise mouths,

00:31:59.300 --> 00:32:01.950
